Q1: Difference between a t-test and a z-test
t-test:

Used when sample size is small (n < 30) or population standard deviation is unknown.

Example: Comparing the mean test score of a class (n = 20) to a national average.

z-test:

Used when sample size is large (n â‰¥ 30) and population standard deviation is known.

Example: Comparing the average height of 100 students to a known national average when population std. dev is known.

Q2: One-tailed vs Two-tailed tests
One-tailed test:

Tests for a direction (e.g., > or <).

Example: Checking if new drug is more effective than old one.

Two-tailed test:

Tests for any difference (â‰ ).

Example: Checking if a new teaching method has a different effect, not necessarily better or worse.

Q3: Type I and Type II Errors
Type I Error (False Positive): Rejecting a true null hypothesis.

Example: Concluding a person has a disease when they actually donâ€™t.

Type II Error (False Negative): Failing to reject a false null hypothesis.

Example: Concluding a drug has no effect when it actually does.

